  "prompt": "How is Eid al Fitr celebrated?",
  "response": "Eid al Fitr is celebrated by Muslims worldwide to mark the end of Ramadan, the Islamic holy month of fasting. Here are some key ways it is celebrated:\n\n1. Prayer\n- Special congregational prayers are held in mosques or large open areas\n- These prayers are typically performed early in the morning\n\n2. Family and Community Gatherings\n- Families and friends come together to celebrate\n- People often wear new or special clothing\n- Festive meals are shared\n\n3. Giving Gifts\n- Children often receive gifts, money, or sweets\n- People exchange presents with family and friends\n\n4. Food and Feasting\n- After a month of fasting, special meals are prepared\n- Traditional foods vary by region and culture\n- Sweet dishes are particularly common\n\n5. Charitable Giving\n- Muslims are encouraged to give Zakat al-Fitr (charitable donations)\n- This helps ensure less fortunate people can also celebrate\n\n6. Decorations\n- Homes and streets are often decorated\n- People may use lights, banners, and festive decorations\n\n7. Greeting and Wishing\n- People wish each other \"Eid Mubarak\" (Blessed Eid)\n- Greetings and well-wishes are exchanged\n\nCelebrations can vary across different cultures and regions, but these are common practices during Eid al Fitr.",
